abstract: Flat tire, with music. Stay with Wayne Morris-Bette Davis-Eddie Robinson.
snippet: Flat tire, with music. Stay with Wayne Morris-Bette Davis-Eddie Robinson.
lead_paragraph: The last thing you might think Elvis Presley is qualified to do is act a diffident amateur boxer who turns out to be a tiger in the professional ring. And you might well persist in that opinion after seeing him in "Kid Galahad," a sportive remake of an old Wayne Morris picture, which came to the Astor yesterday.Mr. Presley is certainly no model for a statue of Hercules, and his skill at projecting an illusion of ferocity is of very low degree. The expanses of flesh that he exposes when he gets into boxing togs are a fair indication that most of his muscles have come from punching a guitar, and his pout when he clouts a rival bears no resemblance to a killer's slit-mouthed sneer.Furthermore, the proclivity assigned him by his genius and William Fay's script of expressing himself at odd moments in conspiciously un-pugnacious songs, brought up from what seems a ruptured larynx, does not endow him with a gladiatorial air.No, we'll have to agree that Mr. Presley does not make a very convincing pug.But somehow this clique-ridden picture, which has its origin in an ancient novel by Francis Wallace that has been drawn upon (or snitched from) for any number of Golden Boy films, makes a moderately genial entertainment. It's not explosive, but it has the cheerful top of a lightly romantic contrivance that ranges between comedy and spoof.For this we can thank the other actors who played their roles ardently and Phil Karlson, who has directed at a brisk and deceptive pace.Gig Young is attractively wicked as a Catskill hotel-keeping heel who tries to lead the young boxer to slaughter so he himself may drink. Lola Albright is charmingly solicitious as Mr. Young's disillusioned girl and Joan Blackman is pretty and submissive as the last who falls for Mr. Presley's songs. Charles Bronson, Ned Glass and Robert Emhardt make good training-camp characters.For a film about a singing prize-fighter (which is silly enough) it will do.

abstract: "Constantine and the Cross," which opened in neighborhood theaters yesterday, is one of those ponderous costumed tabloids that's trampled history to death, and turned what's left of its fragments into boring banalities.Cornel Wilde, as the great emperor who established Christianity in Rome, walks through this key role as if he were an earnest fellow who had just been inspired in Sunday School. Belinda Lee is the dark and toothsome beauty who finds the paganism of Rome okay, and Christine Kaufmann is the ashblonde Christian maiden whose martyrdom impresses Constantine.There is the usual mob of Italian extras wigged out in funny clothes and pushing and bumping one another as little as necessary to give an appearance of motion to the so-called battle scenes. As usual with these cut-rate spectaculars, the color is terrible and the dubbed English dialogue inserted for the Italian actors in the cast is fractured Bronx.

abstract: Oddly biased, sourish drama of Eurasian heel. Japan looks fine.
snippet: Oddly biased, sourish drama of Eurasian heel. Japan looks fine.
lead_paragraph: It is odd that a fellow as disagreeable as the one Laurence Harvey plays in the film called "A Girl Named Tamiko" which arrived yesterday at the Music Hall, is as admired as he is by the sleek young women played by Martha Hyer and France Nuven in this film.He is, by all that is evident, an unmitigated boor — a man who frankly ackowledges that he thinks only of himself. Being the son of a Russian father and a Chinese mother, and living in Tokyo, he ruefully uses the anomaly of his birth to justify his bitterness.His sole and consuming ambition is to get to the United States, where he hopes to turn to advantage his skill at photography. To this end, he will use anybody, including the beauteous Miss Hyer, who has good friends in high positions among her fellow Americans in Tokyo.At first, she icily resists him. But then suddenly she falls for him — goes absolutely daffy about him. This is odd, indeed.Odd, too, is the beaming admiration that Miss Nuyen develops for this boor. She is the gentle daughter of aristocratic Japanese, not used to his kind of self-seeking. But she falls for him like a ton of bamboo. Indeed her admiration seems to burgeon when he coolly betrays a trust she has arranged for him to see a Japanese painter.It is hard to follow the reasons or be impressed by these romantic terms.Odd, too, is the fact that all the Americans we see are silly to downright vicious types, while most of the Japanese are forthright, courteous and charming. Miss Hyer is a seamy, scheming shrew and the fellow with whom she shares quarters (Gary Merrill) is a rugged, calculating tough. A visiting American, Steve Brodie, is the worst sort of callow tourist type and his wife, Lee Patrick, is the usual dreary hanger-on.In short, this solemn drama that Edward Anhalt has written from a novel by Ronald Kirkbride and that John Sturges has directed is a lot of oddly slanted groping for a hackneyed romantic point and the only thing fetching about it is some of its handsome scenery.There are beautiful shots of such places as the graceful Toshogu Shrine at Nikko, the great Todaiji Temple with its huge image of Buddha inside and Lake Biwa near Kyoto, in addition to some interesting shots of Tokyo. The film is in color and wide screen, but, alas, the conception of romance represented is as monotonous and and narrow as the narrowest mind in Hollywood.

abstract: Italians resist German occupation forces.
snippet: Italians resist German occupation forces.
lead_paragraph: A sudden and throbbing nostalgia for the great Italian neo-realist films at the end of World War II is stirred by "The Four Days of Naples." This new Italian documentary film, or historical re-enactment, opened at the Beekman last night.Here again, in this remembrance of the way the people of Naples behaved when General Badoglio signed an armistice with the Allies in September, 1944, and they happily thought the war was over, rumbled the same blood-chilling thunder that growled in Rosselini's "Open City" and "Paisan" the same fearsome rumors of social chaos as were in De Sica's "Shoe Shine" and "The Bicycle Thief."Suddenly, almost 20 years after those sad and savage days, we see the unquestionable furor of the people of a city going wild, first with joy at their illusory liberation, and then with terror when they realized they are trapped. We see the bone-crunching reality of startled celebrants cracked on the head with the butts of Nazi rifles, the horror of a smiling sailor shot on the steps of the university as a brutal warning to the mob, the dread of Neopolitan wives and mothers as their men are rounded up for shipment into Nazi slavery.And then, as if all this were something that only happened yesterday, so tautly and with such evidence of authenticity has it been re-enacted under the direction of Nanni Loy, we see the birth of the Italian Resistance and the sudden, spontaneous surge of the sniping, bomb-tossing guerrilla warfare that made Naples an epic battlefield.There are no stars in this picture — only a few minor actors who appear in the several roles of more or less key participants in the violent activities. In the broad sweep of Signor Loy's camera, the people of Naples are the stars — a great swirling mass of individuals that howled with terror, grief and defiance.Almost every shot in every sequence is packed with eloquence and meaning. Dozens of them lacerate the senses and remain etched in memory: the shot of a hungry mother giving her last bit of food to her little boy; the look on the face of the young sailor when he realizes that he is doomed; the appearance of the first resistance fighters displaying the bodies of slain companions through the streets, crying to the people to join in combat.These are pictures we won't forget.Evidently, the inspiration of such profound emotions is the basic intent of this production. It was certainly designed by Signor Loy and its producer, Goffredo Lombardo, to make the older people of Italy feel again the fire of courage they felt in those dark moments, and to make the younger people know what it was.There isn't the slightest question that it accomplishes this intent.

abstract: Contrived, far-fetched suspense. Little merit except Loren looks.
snippet: Contrived, far-fetched suspense. Little merit except Loren looks.
lead_paragraph: Sophia Loren is given very little opportunity to display her acknowledged talent for acting in Anatol Litvak's new film, a melodrama called "Five Miles to Midnight," which opened yesterday at the Astor, the Murry Hill and other theaters in the metropolitan area.To be sure, she is called upon to tussle with an ugly moral problem when her spouse, a no-good American youngster played by Anthony Perkins, turns up in their Paris apartment after he is supposed to have been killed in an airplane crash. He demands that she not only conceal him, but also that she defraud an insurance company of the large accident policy he had taken on his life.But it is a rather contrived and far-fetched problem. It is a tawdry one, to say the least. And it doesn't require acting so much as merely walking grimly through the role.Miss Loren does this to perfection. She's the best walker on the screen. The only trouble is that when she walks, even grimly, it confuses the emotional atmosphere. It takes the viewer's mind off her problem. This happens often in this film.But it doesn't really make much difference, because it isn't much of a problem that she has. It is more the projection of an intrigue in which her character lets herself be involved. There are a few tight, suspenseful moments in it, such as when the concierge almost catches Mr. Perkins in the apartment with Miss Loren.There is also a rather grisley climax that Miss Loren plays with widely staring eyes. But it is all a bit fraudulent and tedious.Mr. Perkins is synthetic, too, and Gig Young stumbles around like a playful birddog. He doesn't get what's going on until the end. And then is he surprised and disillusioned. His moment of shock is the most touching thing in the film.As though to remind the New York public that Miss Loren isn't really bad—that she has a cheerful side that she very much likes to display—another picture with this actress opened in the neighborhood theaters yesterday. It is a sumptious costume film, called "Madame," in which she plays the role of the legendary French coquette, created by Emile Moreau and Victorien Sardou in their play called "Madame Sans-Gene."Actually, it doesn't call upon her to exercise her talents any more than she does in her role in "Five Miles to Midnight." It only calls upon her to show more of herself, more frankly and freely and with a great deal more chumminess and cheer.As the lusty Parisian laundress who washes Napoleon's shirts when he is just the "little corporal," then marries one of his favorite officers and rises to high station with him while never losing her washerwoman ways, Miss Loren breezes through it, sassy, vulgar and gay, squabbling with Napoleons haughty sisters and flirting with the men. It is a straight vehicle for her appearance, and she rides it luxuriously.Robert Hossein, a rugged French actor, plays the military roughneck she weds, Julien Bertheau plays Napoleon and Gabriella Pallotta and Annalia Gade play his nasty sisters as dutiful supporting actors.The staging is colorful and dubbed English dialogue is poor.

abstract: Heavy, symbolic hooey set in a brothel. What this one needs is Laurel and Hardy.
snippet: Heavy, symbolic hooey set in a brothel. What this one needs is Laurel and Hardy.
lead_paragraph: A ribald and hollow mockery of man as a vain and vicious beast is all that comes clear in the movie that Ben Maddow and Joseph Strick have made from Jean Genet's play, "The Balcony," which sizzled off Broadway a few years back. And it's not very witty mockery, either, when you cut it clear of the shock of the tawdry grotesqueries in this picture that opened yesterday at the DeMille, Baronet and other theaters in the metropolitan area.The mockery is got from showing various men playing vain and childish games that give them illusions of being important. They play their games in a house of ill-repute, situated in a city where a riot or revolution is going on.One man plays at being a general, another a bishop, another a judge—each with an inmate of the brothel to assist his ridiculous conceit. Then the chief of police of the city enters and lengthily complains because nobody in this house of illusion wants to play at being him. And finally the madam of the establishment mocks the whole bunch by pretending she is a queen.If there is some symbolic meaning to be gotten from this labored mockery, besides the obvious implications that man lives by unwholesome dreams in a world bent on final destruction, it fails to emerge. And if that is the meaning, it's hardly worth sitting through the film to get.Peter Faulk does provide a few bright moments of elaborate travesty on the pompous airs of an official in the role of the chief of police. And Lee Grant is briefly amusing as a secretary in the brothel who wants to return to being one of the girls.Kent Smith, Jeff Corey and Peter Brocco are broad but mirthless in the role of the various men, and Shelly Winters plays the madam with an air of contempt.Mr. Strick's direction is heavy for such a bold conceit. We must say the attitude of Miss Winters is one with which we can relate.
